-- Civilopedia

INSERT OR IGNORE INTO LocalizedText 
       (Language, Tag,                                       Text) 
VALUES ('en_US',  'LOC_PEDIA_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_NYGUITA_ARGENTINA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1',  'The first Europeans to arrive in the region were the Portuguese in the early 16th century, soon followed by the Spanish. Successful colonization only started at the end of the century under the Viceroyalty of Peru. Although Buenos Aires was in a prime location for a port, all shipments went through the capital of the viceroyalty: Lima. This lead to a rise in contraband in the region. In 1776, the Spanish created the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata, made from southern bits of the previous Viceroyalty to try better organize the region, both commercially and militarily. However this reform arrived too late and did not suffice to quell the demands of the population.'),
       ('en_US',  'LOC_PEDIA_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_NYGUITA_ARGENTINA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2',  "After the battle of Trafalgar, Spain's dominence in sea was bare and therefore, the Spanish throne could not support or assert their authority in their American colonies. When Great Britain tried to invade Buenos Aires in 1806, the local population stood up and repealed the invasion. With a great victory achieved without the help of mainland Spain, this gave the idea that independence was achievable. This spark led to many revolutions attempts to remove local authorities but without success. Argentina had to wait until the Napoleon's conquest of Spain during the Peninsular war before a successful revolution in May of 1810."),
       ('en_US',  'LOC_PEDIA_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_NYGUITA_ARGENTINA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3',  'During the first years of the War of Independence, the newly-created United Provinces of the Río de la Plata was led by the Primera Junta who started waging war against the remains of the royalists in other cities, replacing the local governments with more juntas, becoming the Junta Grande. The high number of members and factions in the Junta, however, slowed down its work as an executive power and a new system of government was created with the First triumvirate: Manuel de Sarratea, Feliciano Chiclana and Juan José Paso. This triumvirate soon replaced the local juntas with governors from Buenos Aires and disestablished the Junta Grande and their proposition for a constitution.'),
       ('en_US',  'LOC_PEDIA_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_NYGUITA_ARGENTINA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4',  'In the mean time, followers of Moreno, a radical independentist, joined José de San Martin, a veteran of the Peninsular war. With other generals, they ousted the First triumvirate on October 8th 1812 and instaured a Second triumvirate. In 1816, the Congress of Tucuman was held, finally declaring the independence of the United Provinces. However, a disagreement upon the type of government and the opposition between Unitarians and Federalists nullified the efforts of the 1819 constitution and a civil war broke out, leading to the defeat of the Unitarian Party. Argentina would not have a president until 1824 while during this period, the provinces maintained national unity though treaties, being ruled by caudillos.'),
       ('en_US',  'LOC_PEDIA_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_NYGUITA_ARGENTINA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_5',  'However, due to poor management during the Cisplatine war against Brazil, Rivadavia would resign two years later. Argentina would return into civil war again. Juan Manuel de Rosas would rise as the main figure of this period, asserting the power of Buenos Aires over the other provinces and stabilize the region. But his reluctance to write a new constitution led a revolt that ousted him out of power and in 1853, a new constitution was written and is still applied this day. After reluctance from the province of Buenos Aires, Bartolomé Mitre became the president of the unified nation in 1862.'),
       ('en_US',  'LOC_PEDIA_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_NYGUITA_ARGENTINA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_6',  'During the first years of the Argentine Republic, the nation improved with the modernisation of agriculture, foreign investment, railroads and the Great European immgration wave. After Mitre, Domingo Faustino Sarmiento was elected president and he promoted public education, culture and the modernization of the Army and Navy. However, the nation fell into economic depression due to the Panic of 1873. Most of the economic issues were solved by the Conquest of the Desert, an expedition led by war minister Julio Argentino Roca to expand the national territory southwards by taking those controlled by natives. After a successful campaign, Roca would be elected president in 1880 as the candidate for the National Autonomist Party.'),
       ('en_US',  'LOC_PEDIA_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_NYGUITA_ARGENTINA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_7',  "Between 1880 and 1916, Argentina was led a governing elite called the Generation of '80, creating an age of economic expansion with a liberal economic policy of agricultural exportation inspired by Great Britain. This elite was inspired by the ideas of positivism and social darwinism, believing blindly in order and progress or as Roca campaigned on: 'Peace and Administration'. However, the enormous population expansion due to European immigration gave rise to workers' movements who started asking for better working conditions. A quarter-century later, thanks to the public policies implemented by the Generation of '80, the wave of immigration would lead to a phenomenal social movement and that would bring radicalism to power."),
       ('en_US',  'LOC_PEDIA_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_NYGUITA_ARGENTINA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_8',  "After many socialists and anarchists revolts such as the revolution of the Park and the Radical Revolution of 1905, Roque Sáenz Peña passed the Sáenz Peña Law in 1912, which made the political vote mandatory, secret and universal among males aged eighteen or more. His intention was not to allow the transition of power to the growing socialist Unión Cívica Radical party but to increase public support for the PAN by enabling the universal electoral suffrage. However, the consequence was the opposite of what he intended to accomplish: The following election chose Hipólito Yrigoyen as the president in 1916, ending the oligarchy of conservative forces and the Generation of '80."),
       ('en_US',  'LOC_PEDIA_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_NYGUITA_ARGENTINA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_9',  "While winning the presidency, Hipólito Yrigoyen did not a majority of seats in parliament. As such, only a handful of draft laws were actually voted. But Yrigoyen still instaured the right to strike, minimum wage and collective contracts. In 1919, a series of riots and massacres led by the communists and anarchists took place in Buenos Aires. The uprising was eventually crushed by the police. Following the rise of anarchist thought in the early 1920s, counter-revolutionnary leagues were founded, inspired by the model of Benito Mussolini. After the reelection of Yrigoyen and the Wall Street crash, the movement only grew. On 6 September 1930, a military coup led by the pro-fascist general José Félix Uriburu overthrew Yrigoyen's government and began a period in Argentine history known as the Infamous Decade.");